---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "Return on Investment (ROI) Calculator",
  description: "Stop guessing. Calculate your exact annualized ROI and uncover the true performance of your investments with this interactive tool.",
  category: "tool",
  published: "2026-03-17"
};

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      "headline": "Return on Investment (ROI) Calculator",
      "description": "Stop guessing. Calculate your exact annualized ROI and uncover the true performance of your investments with this interactive tool.",
      "author": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "Westmount Fundamentals"
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is an Return on Investment (ROI) Calculator?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "It is an interactive tool that helps you calculate and plan your investments using historical data and compounding interest formulas."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How accurate is the Return on Investment (ROI) Calculator?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The calculator is mathematically precise based on your inputs. However, future market returns cannot be guaranteed, so conservative estimates are recommended."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Why use an Return on Investment (ROI) Calculator?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "It provides a clear picture of how much you need to save or how your money might grow over time, enabling better financial planning."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Does this Return on Investment (ROI) Calculator account for inflation?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "By default, calculators output nominal values. You should reduce your expected return rate by the expected inflation rate to see real (inflation-adjusted) growth."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How often should I use the Return on Investment (ROI) Calculator?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "It's a good idea to revisit your calculations annually or whenever you have a significant change in income or financial goals."
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
};
---

<SiteLayout site="westmount" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical={`https://westmountfundamentals.com/roi-calculator`} schema={schema}>
  <div style="max-width: 1200px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 20px;">
    <h1 style="color: var(--text-primary); text-align: center;">Return on Investment (ROI) Calculator</h1>

    <div style="background-color: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 30px;">
      <h2 style="color: var(--text-primary); margin-top: 0;">Interactive ROI Calculator</h2>

      <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px;">
        <div>
          <label style="color: var(--text-secondary); display: block; margin-bottom: 5px;">Initial Investment ($)</label>
          <input type="number" id="initial" value="10000" style="width: 100%; padding: 8px; margin-bottom: 15px; background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary); border: 1px solid var(--border-color);" />

          <label style="color: var(--text-secondary); display: block; margin-bottom: 5px;">Monthly Contribution ($)</label>
          <input type="number" id="monthly" value="500" style="width: 100%; padding: 8px; margin-bottom: 15px; background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary); border: 1px solid var(--border-color);" />

          <label style="color: var(--text-secondary); display: block; margin-bottom: 5px;">Years</label>
          <input type="number" id="years" value="20" style="width: 100%; padding: 8px; margin-bottom: 15px; background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary); border: 1px solid var(--border-color);" />

          <label style="color: var(--text-secondary); display: block; margin-bottom: 5px;">Estimated Annual Return (%)</label>
          <input type="number" id="rate" value="8" style="width: 100%; padding: 8px; margin-bottom: 15px; background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary); border: 1px solid var(--border-color);" />

          <button id="calculate" style="background-color: var(--accent-color); color: white; border: none; padding: 10px 20px; cursor: pointer; border-radius: 4px; font-weight: bold; width: 100%;">Calculate</button>
        </div>

        <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; justify-content: center; align-items: center; background-color: var(--bg-color); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 20px;">
          <h3 style="color: var(--text-secondary); margin-top: 0;">Future Value</h3>
          <div id="result" style="font-size: 3rem; color: var(--accent-color); font-weight: bold;">$0.00</div>
          <div style="margin-top: 20px; width: 100%;">
            <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; color: var(--text-primary);">
              <tr>
                <td style="padding: 8px; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color);">Total Contributions</td>
                <td id="total-contributions" style="padding: 8px; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color); text-align: right;">$0.00</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td style="padding: 8px;">Total Interest</td>
                <td id="total-interest" style="padding: 8px; text-align: right;">$0.00</td>
              </tr>
            </table>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div style="color: var(--text-primary); line-height: 1.6;">
      <h2>Understanding the Return on Investment (ROI) Calculator</h2>
      <p>Investing is one of the most powerful ways to build wealth over time. The concept of compound interest allows your money to grow exponentially. This Return on Investment (ROI) Calculator helps you visualize that growth.</p>

      <p>Whether you're starting with a lump sum or contributing a small amount monthly, consistency is key. Let's break down the components of our calculator and how they affect your final outcome.</p>

      <h3>The Magic of Compound Interest</h3>
      <p>Compound interest is often referred to as the eighth wonder of the world. It is the interest on your interest. Over long periods, the majority of your portfolio's growth will come from the compounding effect rather than your principal contributions.</p>

      <p>The formula for compound interest is <br/><strong>A = P(1 + r/n)^(nt)</strong><br/>Where:
      <ul>
        <li><strong>A</strong> is the amount of money accumulated after n years, including interest.</li>
        <li><strong>P</strong> is the principal amount (initial investment).</li>
        <li><strong>r</strong> is the annual interest rate (decimal).</li>
        <li><strong>n</strong> is the number of times that interest is compounded per year.</li>
        <li><strong>t</strong> is the time the money is invested for in years.</li>
      </ul>
      </p>

      <h3>How to Use This Calculator</h3>
      <p>To get the most out of the Return on Investment (ROI) Calculator, try running different scenarios. What happens if you increase your monthly contribution by just $100? What if you delay investing by 5 years?</p>
      <p>Common mistakes include overestimating expected returns or underestimating the impact of inflation. Historically, the stock market has returned about 10% annually before inflation, or 7% after inflation. Using conservative estimates (like 6-8%) is generally a safer approach for long-term planning.</p>

      <p>By regularly revisiting your financial plan and adjusting your inputs in this Return on Investment (ROI) Calculator, you can ensure you remain on track to hit your retirement or wealth-building goals.</p>

